## Section 3: Time-Homogeneity

**Q3.1 (E)** A chain has the following time-dependent rule: at even times $n$, $q_{12}^{(n)} = 0.6$; at odd times $n$, $q_{12}^{(n)} = 0.2$. Is this chain time-homogeneous? Is it still Markov? Explain.

**Q3.2 (M)** Suppose a Markov chain is time-inhomogeneous with matrices $Q_0, Q_1, Q_2, \ldots$ Write down the expression for $P(X_3 = j \mid X_0 = i)$ in terms of the matrices $Q_0, Q_1, Q_2$. Why does this not equal $(Q_0)^3_{ij}$ in general?

**Q3.3 (M)** A weather model uses the summer matrix

$$
Q_S = \begin{pmatrix} 0.8 & 0.15 & 0.05 \\ 0.3 & 0.5 & 0.2 \\ 0.2 & 0.3 & 0.5 \end{pmatrix}
$$

and the winter matrix

$$
Q_W = \begin{pmatrix} 0.5 & 0.2 & 0.3 \\ 0.2 & 0.4 & 0.4 \\ 0.1 & 0.2 & 0.7 \end{pmatrix}
$$

If today (a summer day) the weather is Sunny, compute the probability that the weather is Rainy two days from now, assuming the next day is also summer but the day after is the first winter day. Show your working.

**Q3.4 (H/P)** Prove that if a time-homogeneous Markov chain has stationary distribution $\pi$ satisfying $\pi Q = \pi$, then $\pi Q^n = \pi$ for all $n \geq 1$.

