## Section 5: The Transition Matrix Q

**Q5.1 (E)** Determine which of the following matrices can be a valid transition matrix. For those that cannot, state why.

$$
A = \begin{pmatrix} 0.5 & 0.5 \\ 0.3 & 0.8 \end{pmatrix}, \quad
B = \begin{pmatrix} 0.4 & 0.6 \\ 0.7 & 0.3 \end{pmatrix}, \quad
C = \begin{pmatrix} 1.0 & 0.0 \\ 0.0 & 1.0 \end{pmatrix}, \quad
D = \begin{pmatrix} 0.5 & 0.3 \\ 0.4 & 0.6 \end{pmatrix}
$$

**Q5.2 (M)** The transition matrix of a 3-state chain is

$$
Q = \begin{pmatrix} 0.4 & 0.5 & 0.1 \\ 0.2 & 0.6 & 0.2 \\ 0.0 & 0.3 & 0.7 \end{pmatrix}
$$

(a) Write out in words what $q_{23} = 0.2$ means.

(b) Write out in words what $q_{31} = 0.0$ means.

(c) The chain is currently in state 2. Write down the full probability distribution of $X_{n+1}$ as a row vector.

(d) Can the chain move from state 3 to state 1 in exactly two steps? Compute the probability.

**Q5.3 (M)** Let $Q$ be an $M \times M$ transition matrix. Prove that $Q^2$ is also a transition matrix (i.e., all entries are non-negative and all rows sum to 1).

**Q5.4 (H)** A transition matrix $Q$ has $q_{ij} > 0$ for all $i, j \in S$. Show that every row of $Q^n$ satisfies $\min_{i,j}(Q^n)_{ij} \geq (\min_{i,j} q_{ij})^n > 0$. What does this imply about the long-run behaviour of the chain?

