## Section 6: Distributions and the Row-Vector Convention

**Q6.1 (E)** The initial distribution is $p^{(0)} = \begin{bmatrix} 0.5 & 0.3 & 0.2 \end{bmatrix}$ and

$$
Q = \begin{pmatrix} 0.4 & 0.5 & 0.1 \\ 0.2 & 0.6 & 0.2 \\ 0.0 & 0.3 & 0.7 \end{pmatrix}
$$

Compute $p^{(1)} = p^{(0)} Q$ explicitly. Verify the result sums to 1 and interpret $p^{(1)}_2$ in words.

**Q6.2 (M)** Continuing from Q6.1, compute $p^{(2)}$ two ways:

(a) By computing $p^{(1)} Q$.

(b) By computing $p^{(0)} Q^2$ (first compute $Q^2$, then multiply).

Verify both methods give the same answer.

**Q6.3 (M)** Starting from state 1 with certainty (i.e., $p^{(0)} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix}$), show that $p^{(1)}$ is exactly row 1 of $Q$. Explain geometrically why this must always be true.

**Q6.4 (M)** A student uses the column-vector convention and writes $p^{(1)}_\text{col} = Q\, p^{(0)}_\text{col}$ (without transposing). Using

$$
Q = \begin{pmatrix} 0.7 & 0.3 \\ 0.4 & 0.6 \end{pmatrix}, \quad p^{(0)}_\text{col} = \begin{pmatrix} 0.2 \\ 0.8 \end{pmatrix}
$$

compute what the student gets. Then compute the correct answer using $Q^\top p^{(0)}_\text{col}$. Explain in index notation why the student's formula uses $q_{ji}$ instead of $q_{ij}$.

**Q6.5 (H/P)** Prove that if $p^{(0)}$ is a probability distribution (non-negative entries summing to 1) and $Q$ is a transition matrix, then $p^{(n)} = p^{(0)} Q^n$ is a probability distribution for every $n \geq 1$.

