## Section 10: Synthesis and Proofs

**Q10.1 (M)** Starting from the definition of the transition matrix and the Markov property alone, derive the formula $p^{(n)} = p^{(0)} Q^n$ for the distribution at time $n$. Your derivation should make clear exactly where the Markov property and time-homogeneity are each used.

**Q10.2 (M)** Two Markov chains $(X_n)$ and $(Y_n)$ on the same state space $S$ are run independently. Define $Z_n = (X_n, Y_n)$. Show that $(Z_n)$ is a Markov chain on $S \times S$ and write down its transition matrix in terms of the individual transition matrices $Q_X$ and $Q_Y$.

**Q10.3 (H/P)** Let $Q$ be an $M \times M$ transition matrix. Prove that 1 is always an eigenvalue of $Q$ with right eigenvector $\mathbf{1} = (1, 1, \ldots, 1)^\top$. Then show that all other eigenvalues $\lambda$ satisfy $|\lambda| \leq 1$. (*Hint for the second part: use the fact that $Q$ is a stochastic matrix and consider the action of $Q$ on a vector achieving its maximum entry.*)

**Q10.4 (H)** Suppose a Markov chain on $\{1, 2, \ldots, M\}$ has the property that $Q^n \to \Pi$ as $n \to \infty$, where every row of $\Pi$ is the same vector $\pi$. Show that:

(a) $\pi Q = \pi$ (i.e., $\pi$ is a stationary distribution).

(b) $\pi$ is a probability distribution (entries non-negative, sum to 1).

(c) For any initial distribution $p^{(0)}$, $p^{(0)} Q^n \to \pi$ as $n \to \infty$.

**Q10.5 (H/P)** (Uniqueness of the stationary distribution under irreducibility.) Suppose $Q$ is a transition matrix such that for every pair of states $i, j$ there exists $n \geq 1$ with $(Q^n)_{ij} > 0$ (i.e., the chain is irreducible). Prove that there is at most one probability distribution $\pi$ satisfying $\pi Q = \pi$. (*Hint: suppose $\pi$ and $\mu$ are both stationary and consider $\pi - \mu$; use the fact that $(\pi - \mu)Q^n = \pi - \mu$ for all $n$ and that the entries must remain bounded.*)

